              li Command line usage
              li Capybara
              li Heroku
              li Git and GitHub
              li TDD testing
              li Pair programming
              li Object Oriented Programming
        hr

        p.
          Some of these I know pretty well, of others I have just a passing knowledge. Sometimes
          I feel like a kid surrounded by shiny things, wanting to reach out and explore them all
          at once.

        p.
          The links in the carousel above take you to a few of the programs I've made as part of the
          learning experience. Both the Shell and Memory games demonstrate the use of JavaScript and
          jQuery to dynamically manipulate DOM elements. Quiz-O-Matic adds data sets to the equation.
          And Fireside Chat is my capstone project for the client-side portion of the NSS bootcamp.
          It utilizes an API call to read and write data to a Firebase database using only client-side Javascript.

        p.
          What I Got is a home media management app meant to catalog books, movies and albums as well
          as home electronics for insurance purposes. It represents both my capstone project for the NSS
          Ruby on Rails portion of the school and my first solo Rails project aside from a couple open
          source projects I contributed to at NSS. What I Got is now a pet project to continue learning
          and tinkering with, beginning with its responsiveness to various devices.

        p.
          The latest addition to the carousel at the top is a link to the WordPress site I just launched.
          I'll use it to explore working with and customizing various WordPress themes, and managing a
          WordPress site in general.

        p.
          What all of this represents, however, is my ability to learn these concepts and turn
          that into practice. I will continue update this site as I learn and accomplish more.

        p — James Nix

